pictures from small moments I never want to forget 

10.22

the complexity of the human experience 💭

I love a good recap, a romanticized version of life’s joyful moments... actually, one of my favorite pieces of content I create regularly is a monthly recap of exactly that. But as the year wraps and my feed is filled of those ~ I can’t help to think of the shadows.

This was year of building both physically and metaphorically for us and with that comes demolition. These summarize bullet points of our (privileged)struggles are a reminder to myself and y o u - that our human experience is complex. Never only painful or beautiful. Embracing both is accepting life ~ it’s letting the shadows dance with the light 🌞

((going over our struggles as a couple to make this was also very insightful, I hope you make time for you and yours to reflect in the good and bad of this year as we lean into the energy of new beginnings 🤍))

some little pieces of the journey✨

11.22

Watch us transform a big red truck 🚒 into our home 🥺

We are getting close to the finish line and still in disbelief with gratitude that we found and are creating a dream we’ve had for years. From here forward it’s the fun details that make it home but the journey here (filled with uncertainty, pain, tears, joy and so much hard work) will forever be the most important and special part.

Cleaning at the end of a full day of projects, making the bed, spending our night talking about the projects we love or the ones that are to come, dreaming of where this truck will take us, hanging out, playing games, listening to the rain on the metal roof (ohhh did I miss this one) 

the little moments of this ~ in between ~ chapter that have brought me more joy than I ever imagined.

crazy how you can build for months and struggle to see the vision come together.. then you spend a few days painting and it shows up ✨✨

a mix of paint for the cabinets and Roman clay for the walls brought our home alive ~ not fully finished yet but already so happy to see this little sanctuary take color 🤍

(nobody asked but one of the most important take aways from the bus for us was don’t skip out on a high quality primer and NEVER buy the cheapest paint! We made both of those mistakes in the bus and it was a nightmare)

#ambulanceconversion #tinyhomeonwheels

here: a magical + random afternoon, with the sun shining through, in between projects, in between life, surrounded by love

~ we’ve done enough resisting, enough questioning, enough wishing we were somewhere else or at a different time. 

this truck, this home, this life 

we chose to love it n o w, exactly how it looks like 🤍

after hiding in the deep shadows of winter ~ this month was a sweet surrender to the seasons 
 
a reminder that not only nature experiences changing weather 

life continues to show us that what you plant needs t i m e to bloom 💫

d a y 5 of 21 days of updates ~

this is going to be a little series of its own because it was a b i g one.. our shower!

also our last big project of the build and one we kind of procrastinated on because we felt very intimidated — we wanted to truly make this space functional, waterproof and use tile so there was lots new ground to explore 

when we bought the truck we knew immediately that this corner would be our shower and we simply wouldn’t have been able to use it without a custom shower pan from @ourwaytoroam super duper happy we were able to base the shower to the space we had and that we got to use the cool stuff our friends make 🤍

more progress tomorrow!

d a y 6 of 21 days of updates ~

shower starts to look like something!! Although we really wanted tile in this space weight was a big concern for us so we compromised and did two walls with a lightweight PVC tile and we ended up loving the results! Especially the area around the skylight 🥹

Stay tuned tomorrow for the tile!

d a y 7 of 21 days of updates ~ 
 
T i l e is here!!!! And it would have been the same or nearly as fun as it was without Kim @justanotherskoolie 🤍 our little tile fairy - thank you for getting us started and being our site manager - you the best!

Truly one of our fav projects, I had too much fun taking pictures and getting my hands covered in mortar ~

d a y 8 of 21 days of updates ~

👋🏼 grout! cleaning up the tiles and adding grout brought the entire project together in the best way — 

a fun, exciting and full-filling build day that will be always be remembered🤍

crazy how we can be so afraid or anxious of things we don’t know just to go do them and realize it was all silly thoughts/limitations 

#skoolieshower #ambulanceconversion #vanshower

d a y 9 of 21 days of updates ~

I give you the (almost) final version of your wet bath to wrap up the shower updates! So incredible excited about this space, it’s the perfect size for us and has everything we wanted.

Highlights of the space:
-The skylight was a fantastic choice, it opens up what otherwise is a small space and makes it feel hugeee! Plus it gives Zach all the extra headroom for a good shower.
-LOVE our accordion door from @recprousa it’s been so wonderful for the space, plus it brings in lots of light and it super easy to install, use AND clean! 
-We scored our composting toilet for more than half off on Facebook marketplace and are very happy with it, moving it out when showering is easy and we’ve been happily surprised with it coming from a DIY version.

d a y 10 of 21 days of updates~

Didn’t want to miss the opportunity to highlight what quickly has become one of our favorite parts of the truck — our under bed storage!!

I reallllyyy wanted to avoid upper cabinets, not sure why but I don’t like them 🤷🏼‍♀️

this (along with a small wall closet) was our solution for a closet/general storage.. it’s been extremely functional and offers SO much storage space! It’s also Miski approved so we are winning! 

Have you seen this before? Would you consider it for your rig?

d a y 11 of 21 days of updates~

Want to play a little game? Swipe to see alll the little projects in between ~ getting to this stage felt like the light at the end of the tunnel. 

For we were finally home 🤍

We like to call this our ‘base model’ for there will always be a long list of projects to finish, things we want to change/add/replace but for now this right here is our space and that is simply the most beautiful feeling

d a y 12 of 21 days of updates~

this one is special for a few different reasons🤍

for one we really really wanted a passthrough access, it was one of the top things in our “wish list” when we were searching for our new home — when we bought the 🚒 the pass through had been closed off so re-opening this space was magical (pictures from that day in the carousel). Super excited to have this functionality in our new home!

But what makes it more special is that it is a mini replica to the front door of my grandmas house🤍 I lost my grandma almost two months ago and it was while I was home in Bolivia that this inspiration hit me - I texted Zach about it and I got to come home to the most beautiful gift ✨ it’s a daily reminder of my favorite person and the safe place she gifted me with for so many years🤍

d a y 13 of 21 days of updates~ 

We left our hearts in TN🤍

The last ten months have been some of the most powerful, transformational, healing and unforgettable months of our lives thanks to two (actually five) incredible souls and a special piece of land..

There is so much I could say about what we’ve learned about ourselves, about how lucky we feel having found our people, about the safe space they graciously created for us, about opening our hearts + wounds in community, about life with some big and beautiful puppies, about how truly out of this world special Kim & Ethan are, about sharing life and it’s big changes together, about all that we learned along the way — but anytime I try to write about it I can’t seem to find the right words. 

Maybe because we haven’t fully processed yet all of what this time + space  gifted us; maybe because some people (and places) are so uniquely special that words aren’t enough

Kim once wrote me a letter that said “I’m so happy to be your in-between” and in many ways this time felt like an in-between; but what she or I didn’t know back then is that this chapter is more like it’s own book ~ one that we will continue to grow, learn from and go back too because friendships and experiences like these are gifts you hold on to forever 🤍

d a y 14 of 21 days of updates~

As the build updates come to a close, it’s time for a little appreciation post for the guy who made it all happened🤍

For the last months Zach has dedicated his every single day to building this home. Facing new and scary challenges (hello roof raise), spending hours researching and even driving himself insane with the smallest perfectionist details. 

Thank you for all the hours, sweat, tears, laughs and frustrations along the way ✨ 

Incredibly inspired, proud and thankful to share life with you🤍

A season is closing and looking back to where we started we can hardly recognize ourselves. 

(day 15 of 21 days of updates) 

Maybe I’m starting to sound like a broken record saying how much life has changed for us in the last months — maybe more so because I still don’t really know how to explain it?

We’ve lost and found so many different versions of ourselves in the last 12 months that it feels a bit strange to start feeling like we have arrived to the light at the end of the tunnel. And boyyy was it dark and difficult at times. 

We are not the same people that drove to New Jersey to pick up a truck, nor the same ones that parked down in TN and started the build and I couldn’t even tell you about the ones that lived in a shuttle bus. 

All we know is that somewhere along the way we started getting out of our own way and although we continue to learn how to be better friends, partners and individuals.. we feel closer to a higher/more authentic version of ourselves than ever before.

At the beginning of this build I wrote in a caption “unbuilding ourselves and this big red truck only to re-build again” and I can say this chapter has been exactly that 🤍
the first day of our new adventure🥹

our first hours on the road ✨

(day 16 of 21 days of updates)

Celebrating arriving to the moment and the feeling that started this all. We drove only a few hours, encountered an almost unbelievable amount of reassuring signs along the way and simply felt in our bones (just look at that smile) that this was exactly where we were meant to be. 

Truckyy we are home 🤍

on the road again 

(day 17 of 21 days of updates) 

Snaps from our first full day back on the road - we are so excited to see what this new version of life on the road will bring to us. 

In our reflections we find ourselves wanting to unplan more and more of our lives and journey ~ we want to simply show up with an open mind, an open heart and radical acceptance to what will come our way: detours, people, experiences, places. 

Started our expedition west driving parts of the Mother Road (Route 66) and we couldn’t think of a better road to kick off this new adventure 🚒

the first place we called home 

(day 18 of 21 days of updates)

This time around we wanted to make sure we could set ourselves up for success long term ~ and that meant taking it s l o w 

We took the first weeks as an opportunity to ground into our new home, find places for things, collect our feelings, adjust to a full-time job on the road and finish some projects.

this time was so precious to us, a chance to reconnect with this lifestyle, nature and each other 🤍

1426 miles in 40 west 

(day 19 of 21 days of updates) 

This is our second trek west and our first time through parts of Route 66. There is something different about this road, you can find it’s history in every corner and roadside attraction. The energy of the thousands of people that took this road throughout the years seeking adventure and new beginnings dances through the air. 

It felt fitting to start our journey here, we felt incredibly inspired - ready to start our own expedition. To be shaped by the places, people and stories we found along the way ~

we lived in a parking lot for 6 days 

(day 20 of 21 days of updates)

It happened, our first mechanical issue. We had some old parts starting to act up (leaking) so we knew it was better to stop and take care of it. But like almost any diesel mechanic shop we’ve encountered we had to wait for an appointment and then a few extra days for parts (like any good ol vehicle).

So, we parked up in a Cracker Barrel parking lot to wait it out and cocooned into our home. We made the most out of our time and free public transportation to get all the supplies we needed to make our cushions! 

My favorite part of spending most of our time inside our little 14 foot box? Photographing the light as it dances through the house ✨

d a y 21 of 21 days of updates ~

We’ve been on the road for 42 days and today (5.12.23) marks one year since we officially became the owners of this big red truck 🚒

Wouldn’t change a thing - feeling extremely grateful and excited for this new adventure!

just three internationals exploring the US one dirt road at a time ~

Let me explain..

Our truck is an ‘International’ and both me and Miski 🐈 are from Bolivia 🇧🇴 

So, Zach’s new thing has been to call us the three internationals

(Great band name?) 

But in a more personal note, it reminds me how unexpectedly grounding it’s been to have Miski with us knowing she was born only a few blocks away from where I was born. She is my little home buddy, we speak Spanish to each other and have cultivate such a special bond. It wasn’t until recent years that I started feeling ‘homesick’ (although I’ve been living in the US for 9 years!) and lately when it hits she’s been my little dose of home 🤍

📸 from the first day of my 28th turn around the sun 

6.1.23

My third birthday on the road, in fact it was on my birthday three years ago that we left Ohio and officially started our adventure. Over these three years I’ve lost and found so many versions of myself. 

Excited to turn this chapter as a happier, healthier, more authentic version of myself. 

Cheers to more growth + more years of waking up in little homes on wheels, down dirt roads, living life in our terms and to fullest.

little moments from camp ⛺️ 

our first camp with friends in the new rig was everything we could have asked for and missed plus some more.. like all of us almost getting stuck on the way out 😂

Grateful to have crossed roads with these incredible souls 

(Now on a more serious note, how would you finish this joke: A shuttle bus, an ambulance and a sprinter drive into a bar ..)

& its even more accurate considering we turned a fire truck 🚒 into our full-time traveling home 🥹

Forever and ever grateful for parents that have been nothing but supportive of me and my wildest dreams.. even when I told them I wanted to ditch my normal life for life on the road or that I wanted to live in a ship and go around the world 🥲they have and continue to be my biggest and most important support system, encouragement and inspiration. 

Grateful they make what is otherwise difficult and scary a little bit easier 🫶🏼

— do it afraid. 

For many years I held the believe that the things that were meant to be wouldn’t feel scary, that I would find comfort and courage in “knowing” that I was on the right path. Whatever that even means. I’m realizing more and more that it s h o u l d feel scary, that fear will always creep in and make home in any open space. 

I’ve promised myself to do it, whatever it is — even (and more particularly) if I have to do it afraid.

& I hope you do too.

what a month 🎢 

some of the happiest times we’ve had on the road: like celebrating a birthday in the mountains and sharing camp life with my parents 

to the most difficult experience of being in the right place at a tragic time. 

Through it all I keep finding the reminder of how precious life is, how every experience is there for a reason and how the only thing that we can do is make the most of each day with presence, gratitude and joy. 

This month will be one of those unforgettable ones that I write about in a book one day 💭

There is more to you than yesterday (or tomorrow) 💭

One of the biggest lessons this 🚒 has thought us is that 

there is you ~ n o w.

🎨 Your gentle reminder that creating art in any form  is not limited to being good at it or having done it your whole life. Just have f u n. 

Create to create, to be curious, to experiment, to try, to do something different, to be present. 

Our newest date night is drawing in our little notebooks with soft pastels. It’s become a fun tradition to capture the places we call home and have a somewhat weekly excuse to just play, let our inner child come out and try something different. Are we good at it? Not really, but it’s so much fun!! 

Is there an art medium you always wanted to try? This is your sign to just do it!!

where and who is home to you? 

Querencia is a Spanish word that represents a metaphysical concept of “belonging”. Although there is no exact translation, this word refers to a feeling - sometimes a place or a person - that brings you home. 

“A place where one draws inspiration and strength from.. a place where one feels most comfortable and true”

This is my Querencia: the mountains, a home we built with our own hands, a person that chooses to do life with me everyday, our kitty and my relationship with myself 🤍

Just a little different 🚒💭

Reaching a point where it feels like we *actually* completed our build (although our list of things to finish and do still has lots of items left) but starting to look back on where we started to simply celebrate the journey ✨

All the feels sharing this first transformation video 🥹

Places we’ve called home: august edition ~

postcards from Glacier ⛰️ 

& a few words ✍🏼

when we left TN, Kim was too kind to let me steal her old camera and since I’ve been in a mission to learn how to use it — 
this is my first camera, up to this point I filmed, captured and edited everything on my phone. 

All those years I had the purpose to prove to myself that I didn’t need the expensive equipment to share my story and to be creative. And I will always stand by that. 

But you also don’t need to limit yourself just to prove a point. At some unknown moment it turned from something that I was proud of to something I held on too just because I was afraid of investing in myself and starting/learning a whole new way of capturing my story. 

I was comfortable in what I knew and could do with my phone and yet I found myself always looking at cameras, saving camera suggestions, reading reviews, saving money for it and never following through. 

Expanding is scary, mostly because it’s uncomfortable. And sometimes we just need the external push. 

So, I hope if you are reading this that you take this story as your push to expand into whatever is next

to that soft whispering inside that has been calling your name 💫

Zach’s POV: Working the overnight shift at beet harvest 
~
One of the things I admire most about Zach is his approach to manual labor. His passion and skill for doing a (hard) manual job and seeing it through; no matter the environment or conditions. The way he pushes his body both physically and mentally is incredibly inspiring to me. 

It’s funny how society has created all these stories to manual labor, making it feel like it’s less valuable than a job that comes with a college degree. What I continue to experience, through Zach, is how this work is not only harder but requires so much more (mentally and physically) than what you learn in a classroom. It requires resilience and I never learned that in books. I’ve learned that through Zach. Through him waking up at 5am every day for his landscaping job, or in watching him layer his body with clothing for night shifts in the winter.

We’ve had so many conversations where we say that Trade School would have been much better fit for him, and the truth is it would have. Instead he carries student loans for a career he won’t have and in reality never really wanted. I share this because I’m tired of the stigma around manual labor and because I’m so proud of the man I share life with. 

I guess this is a long personal way of saying Zach worked the beet harvest this year, these are his pictures and that it’s okay if you don’t “fit” in the one path we are told is the “right” one. 

Because it’s not.

While Zach worked the beet harvest I flew home ~

One of the greatest things I’ve gained in the past 10 years since leaving the place that saw me grow up is perspective. I was born and raised in Cochabamba, Bolivia. A valley surrounded by the Andes mountains in the heart of South America. A small valley of flowers, culture and colors. 

It happened instantly and also slowly, learning to appreciate home that is. Perspective is funny like that, it collects little moments and it starts as soon as you give it space. There are so many things about Bolivia that I used to never pay attention to (or appreciate) but now ache my soul in absence and fill my heart with gratitude. 

These captures are some of those things 🌸

We aren’t meant to go at it alone.

And lucky for us, we’ve gotten to share every bit of this journey with these souls 

from building days to hitting the road 

and everything in between ~ we’ve celebrated milestones, anniversaries, grief, growth and exchanged countless stories 

Needles to say this friendship is special — its rooted in sharing one same (wild) journey in the synchronicity of time 

so grateful this little app crossed our paths ~ and these past days together solidify just how magical it is to share this bond 🌞

f a l l ~ in little moments 

I spent the last hour reading about the science of fall colors, learning that the beauty of yellow, red and orange leaves comes from green chlorophyll dying away. The leaves store all the sugars they can as their last job for the tree before winter; it’s autumns warm days and cool nights that combined create the fall colors we all love and seek. There is no scientific or evolutionary purpose to the change in colors. 

That is what science understands.

But I think there is more to science, wisdom that can’t be explained through the scientific method. 

Fall is the corpse of summer, the dying, the letting go.. difficult seasons that are often associated with darkness yet nature chooses to display them in beautiful color. 

I find purpose in that choice.

but maybe that’s just me. 

~
#theartofslowliving #theartofnoticing #lessonsfromnature #liveintentionally
